summary.seg: This mid-14th century working text manuscript transmits the so-called 'Byzantine triad' of three plays of Euripides (b. c. 480, d. 406 BC), selected for study in Byzantine schools: Hecuba, Orestes and Phoenician Women.

The first section (ff. 1r-33v) comprises Hecuba and Orestes ll. 1-133, and the text follows the recension (i.e. redaction) of the Byzantine grammarian Manuel Moschopoulus Moschopoulos, Manuel, approximately 1265?- (13th-14th century; see Turyn (1957), p. 123-124).

The second section (ff. 34r-107v) contains Orestes ll. 134-end and Phoenician Women, in the recension of Byzantine grammarian Thomas Magistros Thomas, Magistros, active 1310-1327 (13th-14th century), and is accompanied by scholia of the same scholar.
The order of quires from ff. 41r to 68v is inverted, and an English hand has noted the order of lines.

Richard Porson Porson, Richard, 1759-1808 , Regius Professor of Greek at Cambridge (b. 1759, d. 1808), used this manuscript (siglum Cant) in his edition of Euripides' tragedies (see the second edition, 1802).
J. Diggle designated the manuscript with siglum Mm in his edition of Phoenician Women (Oxford, 1994); the manuscript is also designated as Zx for scholia by Günther (1995).
The fragments that are now Cambridge, University Library, MS Add. 2753.1 once served as endleaves to this manuscript before the present binding.

support.material:
ff. 1r-108r Western paper, folded in octavo. Watermarks: Pot ( 70 35 ) on the gutter comparable to Briquet, 12468-9 ;
Homme ou Femme, Forgeron ( 85 65 ) on the gutter, comparable to Briquet, 7556 . The majority of those examples are dated to the middle of the 14th century.

Conjoint outermost bifolio of quires 1, 5, and 7: ff. [i] recto and 8r, 33r and 40r, 53r and 60r These folios were added to quires 1, 5, and 7 to fill the loss of original folios. Western paper, folded in octavo. Watermark: Monts ( 40 90 ) near the spine comparable to Harlfinger, Monts 72-89 and Briquet, Monts 11853-72 . The majority of those examples are dated from the end of the 14th century and the first half of the 15th century.

supportDesc.foliation: [a-b] + i-ii + 1-108 + [c-d]. Modern foliation in pencil in Arabic numerals in the top right-hand corner, recto.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 13 quires: 11 quaternions, one quinion and one sexternion. The order of quires 6, 7, and 8 (ff. 41r-68v) is inverted (see above).

signatures.p: A discontinuous sequence of quire signatures in pencil in Arabic numerals is added in the bottom right-and corner of the first folio, recto of quires 2-3, 5-11:
ff. 9r, 17r, 33r, 41r, 53r, 61r, 69r, 77r, 85r. The sequence reflects the current state of the manuscript.

condition.p: In generally fair condition. The top half of f. 6 is torn away, with loss of text; portion of the outer margin of f. 96r is cut away, with loss of scholia; f. 101r is torn in two and a portion of margin cut away, with likely loss of scholia; a scrap of f. 105r (height 40 mm, width 90 mm) is cut away, with loss of text (added in margin on f. 105r).
Due to a loss of original outermost bifolios of quires 1, 5, and 7, ff. [i] recto and 8r, 33r and 40r, 53r and 60r) were substituted in the mid-15th century with cleaner western paper.
There are occasional stains, worm holes, and some water damage.

layoutDesc.layout:
Ff. 1r-108v: written space 175 115
Main text between 15 and 24 lines per page. The scholia that accompany the main text have a very variable number of lines per page and the arrangement is rarely (e.g. f. 61r) disorganized, because of the overlap of interventions.

handNote.p: The main text is a mixed minuscule in an upright, scribal hand, in brown ink script.

There is moderate variation in letter size. Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings usually appear only at the end of lines, but occasionally elsewhere (common abbreviation of μεν). Breathings are curved and mute iota is absent. The double grave accent is in frequent use.

The small majuscules beta, gamma, eta, phi are present. Ny is in modern shape, gamma is occasionally high. Theta is both in open and round form, with a point in the horizontal stroke. The sigma telikon is used along with regular sigma in end of words.
Ligatures of kappa with alpha or omega are from the bottom; tau rho ligature in three strokes and overlapping.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper point, lower comma and full stop.
The same hand has written the interlinear glosses and the name of characters in abbreviation in red ink.

The main text is a mixed minuscule in an upright, scribal hand, in brown ink script. Letter size varies frequently. Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings are not limited to the end of lines.
Breathings are curved, circumflex accent is normaly not linked to omega, except in rare cases (e.g. f. 71r). Mute iota is absent.
The majuscules beta, gamma, kappa phi are widely used. Gamma is occasionally high. Beta and omega are large; sigma telikon is not used.
Phi and rho are ligated and overlapping (e.g. φορτίζων f. 70v l. 22). Inclusions of letters within omicron are present.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper point, lower comma and full stop.

decoDesc.decoNote: The tragedies and the argumenta are preceded by headpieces in red ink (f. 1v), with birds (f. 30r) or rectangular headpiece with vegetative ornament in red ink (f. 30v) or brown ink (f. 71v).
The thick red-ink major initials in floral pattern mark the start of a new work or argument, and of most of the scholia in ff. 1-33 (see f. 26v). In f. 30r an head replaces an omicron.
Minor initials written in a thin red-ink uncial within the body of the text.
The manuscript contains sketches drawn in pale brown or red ink in the margins of ff. 7v; human figures: 14r, 14v; birds: 24v; 26v, 30r, 55r.

additions.p: The order of quires 6, 7, and 8 (ff. 41r-68v) is inverted, and an English hand tried to restore the order of lines referring to Joshua Barnes' edition (1694): ff. 40v, 41r, 52v, 53r, 60v, 61r, 68v, 69r.

binding.p: 18th-century binding with pale brown full velvet covering over couched-laminate boards, with plain pastedowns. There is decorative tooling; traces of decorative tooling are present on the board edge.
The title (Euripides Mss) and the classmark are tooled in gold on the spine.

origin.p: The watermarks suggest that the core of the manuscript was produced in Italy in the middle of the 14th century, and that it was restored between the end of the 14th century and the first half of the 15th century.
The characteristics of the scripts indicate that it was produced during the later 14th or earlier 15th century.
Probably the manuscript was produced in different stages, as a working text, and the constituent parts mixed with replacements (cf. Günther 1995, p. 103).

provenance.p: Owned by Jean-Baptiste Hautin Haultin, Jean-Baptiste, approximately 1580-1640 (b. 1580?, d. 1640), who added his ex libris on the front pastedown, and Euripides and on the inner margin manuscrit oriental tres ancien . The manuscript had probably belonged to the French Royal collection, but it left the collection before 1622, when Nicolas Rigault compiled his catalogue.

history.acquisition:
The manuscript contains the bookplate engraved by Pine, John, 1690-1756 John Pine in 1736, to commemorate the donation of books from the library of
John Moore (1646-1714), bishop of Ely Moore, John, 1646-1714 by George I George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 . However, the manuscript has not been traced among records of Moore's library (either Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (c. 1697) or the handwritten supplementary list of Moore's manuscripts, now CUL Oo.7.50.2, compiled by
Thomas Tanner (1674-1735) Tanner, Thomas, 1674-1735 ). A considerable number of books that bear Hautin's name were owned by Moore and came to the Library via George I, so, although conclusive proof is lacking, this seems the most plausible explanation of the book's history.
